Early Risk Alert AI
Pilot Success Criteria Sheet & Workflow Integration Guide
Program	HCP-Facing Clinical Command Center
Pilot Window	90-Day Scoped Pilot Evaluation
Prepared	March 2026 · Milton Munroe, Founder & CEO

1. Pilot Success Criteria Sheet
Objective, pilot phases, success thresholds, and closeout criteria.
Objective
Demonstrate that Early Risk Alert AI can provide supportive patient visibility and prioritization context in a hospital command center while preserving independent clinician judgment, maintaining low burden, and operating under strict governance controls.
Scope Options
•	Phase 1: Retrospective validation on de-identified historical data (lowest risk, recommended first step).
•	Phase 2: Small prospective pilot on 1 unit or command center (with full audit and independent HCP review).
Success Metrics
Category	Measures
Primary Success Metrics	Clinician engagement: ≥65% of supportive review recommendations are opened and independently reviewed.
Operational awareness: ≥20% improvement in command-center team confidence in patient prioritization.
Workflow efficiency: reduction in time spent on manual high-priority patient screening, if measurable.
Safety & Compliance Metrics	100% audit trail completeness for all user interactions.
Zero increase in escalation events or adverse outcomes attributable to the platform.
Full documentation of independent HCP review.
Configurable thresholds and access controls used only under pilot governance rules.
Governance & Technical Metrics	System uptime ≥99% during the pilot period.
All changes tracked through approved change-control.
Successful user provisioning/deprovisioning and data retention/deletion procedures at closeout.
No violations of approved support language or banned claims.
90-Day Success Thresholds
Status	Meaning
Green (Proceed)	Primary metrics met, positive clinician feedback, and full governance compliance. Discuss expansion or the next phase.
Yellow (Extend/Refine)	Partial achievement with no safety issues. Adjust and re-evaluate for 30–60 days.
Red (Orderly Closeout)	Safety concerns or very low engagement. Immediate pilot pause with data return/deletion per policy.
Exit Criteria & Recommended Next Step
•	Clear off-ramp language included in the pilot agreement.
•	All pilot data returned or securely deleted per the data governance policy.
•	Full complaint / issue log and change approval documentation provided to the hospital.
•	Recommended starting point: a no-cost retrospective validation to establish baseline performance before any prospective use.
 
2. Workflow Integration Guide
Short clinician-facing guidance for command-center adoption during pilot evaluation.
Purpose
Early Risk Alert AI is designed as a supportive teammate in the command center — not a replacement for clinical judgment. It provides monitored patient visibility and explainable review context so authorized HCPs can prioritize reviews more efficiently while retaining full independent decision-making.
Key Design Principles
Supportive review context only (never presented as a directive).	Explicit separation between workflow tracking status and clinical recommendations.
Full explainability: review basis, contributing factors, confidence, limitations, data freshness, and “what the software does not know.”	Review-focused naming: Near-Term Review Context, Review Priority Summary, Supportive Review Visibility.
Example Daily Workflow Integration
Step	Application in Command Center
Shift Huddle / Handover (5–10 minutes)	Charge nurse opens the Clinical Command Center, reviews the unit-restricted patient list and Review Priority Summary, opens the explainable panel for high-priority patients, independently reviews the chart, and documents assessment in the EHR.
Routine Monitoring	Teams monitor trends and timeline views during rounds. Data freshness confirms recency. Workflow status such as “reviewed” is tracked separately from supportive clinical context.
Rapid Response / Escalation Review	When a patient appears in the prioritization view, the team uses the explainable panel to understand contributing factors, then performs its own independent clinical assessment before any action.
Important Reminders for Pilot Users
•	The platform supports further clinical evaluation — it does not diagnose or direct treatment.
•	Authorized HCPs must independently review both the patient and the displayed basis for outputs.
•	All interactions are audit-logged for governance and compliance.
Training Support & Expected Benefits
Training Support	Expected Benefits
In-platform section-by-section guidance available via /pilot-docs.
Short clinician-facing demo video available on request.
Pilot user instructions sheet included in the governance bundle.	Improved situational awareness across the command center.
Faster identification of patients who may warrant further review.
Reduced cognitive load through explainable, transparent context.
Maintained clinician autonomy and workflow control.
